                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/14109",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=martel",
                        "name": "martel",
                        "displayName": "Michal Minicki",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Fixed. Zend_Controller_Router_Route consts are now protected vars to allow subclassing.\n\nThanks for your submission, Cristian.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=martel",
                        "name": "martel",
                        "displayName": "Michal Minicki",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-04-11T06:45:30.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-04-11T06:45:30.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/14111",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=avantis",
                        "name": "avantis",
                        "displayName": "Cristian Bichis",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Thanks for update.\n\nJust wondering one thing.\n\nAlways we go for subclassing ? I mean in this case is only needed to set uri_delimiter to new value.\n\nAlso, same case on PDO MSSQL, where is needed to set protected $_pdoType = 'mssql';  to 'dblib' to work properly under *NIX based systems. So basically i need to subclass just for this very small thing. Same on Route thing...\n\nSo, that's a standard way to go on ZF, even if only one parameter change we need to subclass instead of just set this variable ? Subclassing a lot for just very small things if going to add a non-necessary server overhead when working with ZF apps.\n\nOther approach possible, maybe some profiling or something like this... \n",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=avantis",
                        "name": "avantis",
                        "displayName": "Cristian Bichis",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-04-11T07:28:16.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-04-11T07:28:16.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/14114",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=martel",
                        "name": "martel",
                        "displayName": "Michal Minicki",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "> Always we go for subclassing ? I mean in this case is only needed to set uri_delimiter to new value.\n\nYou have to in this case, because url delimiter is used as early as in constructor. If we were to use setters, you would have to use static variables which would make impossible to use two classes with different delimiters. Not to mention subclassing would be render unusable again.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=martel",
                        "name": "martel",
                        "displayName": "Michal Minicki",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-04-11T11:35:20.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-04-11T11:35:20.000+0000"
                }
            ]
        }
